Aug 4 2009 	An adorable place to stay and the owners were exceptionally helpful.	First time traveling to London, I went online to book and was shocked--shocked I tell you!--at how insanely expensive it is. I knew it was gonna be a lot, but GAWD. Thank the stars for Trip Advisor. Upon checking many hotels advertising around 100 pounds (around $170 USD at this writing) and finding reviews revealing they are total tiny and filthy PITS, I had to revise my budget. For 124 pounds I booked a double with two twin beds at the Vicarage. The $210 USD a night price tag nearly killed me, but even before I arrived I knew I had made the right choice.I flew into Luton and didn't realize when I booked that it was way too far away to take a taxi in. I had to get the train to the hotel. I didn't know which to take, but when I called to confirm my room and one of the owners asked where I was flying into, she said I'd need to change trains at least once to get in, and offered to help figure it all out. She figured out which trains I'd need, emailed me the info quickly, and I have to say that even though I could've figured it out on my own it was a lot easier and less stressful to have local help.When I arrived I was thrilled to find the neighborhood awesome, the room charming (and I understand by looking at pics quite large by London standards) and everything spic 'n' span. The only complaints I can think of: the blankets are scratchy wool numbers (but they are O.K. if you just snuggle under the top sheet) and there was some loud construction next door one morning that I didn't get a warning about, but everything else was so nice, these are really small things in comparison.Breakfast is served in a bright downstairs room, and you can have a plate of bacon or kippers with eggs done many ways, toast, and various juices, cereals and (the only downer) canned fruit. Tea or coffee comes with, of course, and even though I can be grumpy and want to keep to myself in the morning (which you can do if you like) I talked to some of the other guests and got some good tips for outdoor markets and such.In a hurry to catch a train to my next destination, I managed to leave some clothing behind in the bureau. I emailed the owners and they offered to mail my things to where I'm staying now, and were very nice about it all too.Overall, I'd say the Vicarage is an excellent place to stay in London, and though expensive (in my world anyway) for London it's a good deal.	
