Jun 24 2008	The Real London	We returned late last evening from London and I wanted to write a Vicarage Gate Hotel review while memory is clearest! First, let me say how lucky we were to stay in this entirely charming and quintessentially English b&amp;b. Having gone to university 27 years ago in London and not having been back for a visit for the past 20 years I was amazed by how London itself has changed. Crazy busy and rare that English is even spoken on the street! The food has become searingly good and the diversity of the population has made for a much more vibrant and exciting place overall.The Vicarage Gate is no exception to the above. What was noteworthy was the attention to details in the hotel. The rooms are beautifully clean -- starched white sheets, comfortable well chosen beds and mattresses (all too rare), gorgeous curtain fabrics and pastel walls, endless high ceilings, shining clean loo and shower. We were in a standard double--no TV or ensuite bathroom, and yes, you will need to be ambulatory, yet the walking up steps has it's rewards with amazing windows and views. This is the type of hotel that really wants you to be self-sufficient in most ways. There is a terrific morning breakfast (7-9am) and the staff is very kind, friendly and accomodating, but this is the place for tourists who like independence, who don't want to have to report on their daily activites to a receptionist. And though the management is quiet it is not non-present. We were meant to change rooms on our fourth night due to a previous booking and the manager tried everything possible to keep us in the same sort of room, which she did. Other travelers are easy to connect with, if you are looking for information and/or conversation. In short, it is a place where you are truly living in a lovely part of London, as a grown-up.We (my daughter and I) loved this hotel, a rare affordable find, which I had last stayed at roughly 25 years ago. It is more beautiful than ever. Thanks to all 