Jan 14 2007	Perfect location great price	Two of us stayed at the Vicarage over Christmas and New Year's. Unbelievable location and incredible value. Residential street with Kensington Palace/Hyde Park on one side and Notting Hill/Kensington High Street neighbourhoods on the other. Very little traffic noise. We found 5 well-priced, tasty restaurants all within 15 minutes walk of the hotel, from Indian to American-style steak place. Lots of good shopping within walking distance. Less than 10 minutes walk in either direction to two separate tube lines. Very quiet, spotless facilities, with professional staff. Efficiently run. No nonsense. There were three toilets and a shower and a separate bathtub (long and deep, with lots of hot water) near our room, so no waiting ever. Windows open for fresh air. Sheets and pillows comfy, mattresses firm. Breakfast has lots of choice, good quality, service is prompt and efficient. Tons of storage in room--armoir and two chests of drawers. Full tea and coffee fixings in room. TV room with books and magazines. Can't recommend it highly enough.	
May 6 2006	Difficult to say the least	Booking a room at the Vicarage is truly a ridiculous process: - they don't take credit cards (uhhh....what?) - they insist you pay the first night up front (you can pay for more nights up front if you wish) - they only take personal checks for the deposit if you book 2+ months in advance (don't get to the bank very often?) - otherwise you have to send travelers checks or some similarly ridiculous thing by mail (super, I can arrange that, and it's cheap too!)Oh and if your at all late they give your room away. Nice.	
May 2 2006	Still Waiting for Peter Pan....	Really, I waited for Peter Pan to come in at night, with the tall windows and ceilings, older furniture, heavy curtains and Victorian feel and decor of the room, the pretty little bacony, this 50 yr old felt like the Wendy-lady. Anyways, to business - advantages of first floor, room 5 which had a big double and a single bed with bath and tv: size of the room - very big especially with what - 20 foot ceilings well-lit by two sweet little chandeliers plus more modern lighting on the wall; would have gladly walked off with the big armoire and triple-mirror vanity table; very clean, well-equipped bathroom (2 hair dryers!) - I love English tubs, they're narrow but long and deep, I could practically float in it and very powerful rain showerhead for shower lovers; pretty breakfast room and very substantial breakfast; just the sheer character of the place; its quietness, both in and outside; excellent transport links; wonderful area for antique hunters and some good little restaurants. On the average side: yep, maybe furnishings are showing wear but given this is a small owner-run property - cut it some slack. I've been in 4-star London hotels that had the nerve to charge more for rooms the size of a coat closet with less amenities. Staff were business-like, also to be expected from a small (and from what we observed, quite busy) hotel. Other advantages, the freedom to let ourselves in and out without any fuss; proximity of Hyde Park and Kensington Palace for a pleasant walk and or tea in the Orangery - the Peter Pan playground there was an absolute thrill for young'uns we saw (even I wanted to get on Hook's ship), and take a little something for the squirrels in Kensington garden, they'll take it right from your hand (but they turn up their little noses at peanuts) not to mention Royal Albert Hall and nearby museums. Would I stay here again? My travelling companion, on her first trip ever outside of Canada gave an unqualified yes. So would I. I'll add pictures later. My final rating - 3.5 out of 5.	
Oct 30 2005	Have Recommended 	My mother, daughter, &amp; I spent 10 nights at the Vicarage Hotel in April. We stayed in a quad room with a bathroom. There was more than enough room for the three of us. Although many listings say there are not tvs in the room, we had a tv and hot drink station (tea, instant coffee, &amp; hot chocolate) in our room. The staff were very helpful and provided us with what every we requested. The breakfast was very filling and good. There were enough possible combinations for breakfast that it was different almost every morning. It was also conveniently located between the High Street Kensington &amp; Notting Hill tube stations.We have already recommended it to family &amp; friends and would love to stay there again. A few reviews of the Vicarage Hotel have been posted erroneously under the Vandon House hotel on TripAdvisor. Please check there for more positive reviews.	
Oct 18 2005	Least favorite place on trip	My husband and I were very much looking forward to the Vicarage, largely from looking at their website, and the 85 stairs from breakfast room to 4th floor didn't worry us. We were excited about the friendly staff and the good value for a double room ($150 in late Sept. '05). However, as it turned out, the staff was neither friendly nor unfriendly, just nonexistent until you went to pay your bill (or at breakfast). We had a double room which was fairly large, but the bedspread was stained, pillow covers had several holes in them and the carpet was worn and appeared dirty. There was not much possibility of spending time in the room to relax anyway, since the room was filled with two beds, a night-table, a chest of drawers and an armoire. The photos on Vicarage's website make the place look quite attractive in a Victorian style, but in the flesh, it's a bit dismal-looking. A trifling example is: none of the dried flower arrangements appeared to have been touched in years so they're covered with dust. The bathroom shower on our floor hardly drained at all so during one's shower, water would be creeping up around one's calves, and not very clean water either. My husband and I enjoy staying at places where the bathroom is down the hall, don't mind stairs, and don't expect 4-star elegance at all. But, we have stayed in hostels in many countries, New Zealand being one, for maybe $30-$40 that had appreciably friendlier and more helpful staff and where the places seemed better looked after. In fact, every place we stayed in on this trip to London, Oxford, Bath and Paris made the Vicarage look worse by comparison. I would not recommend this place and will definitely not return.	
Sep 26 2005	A lovely inn and charming neighborhood	My daughter, traveling companion, and I stayed at the Vicarage the first week of August. Since this inn was highlighted by both Tripadvisor and Rick Steves, we felt secure in our choice, and were not disappointed. The inn is located in a charming neighborhood where we felt very safe walking at just about any time of day or night. We opted for the ensuite and found it to be very clean at all times. Our triple room was on the second floor, furnished tastefully, and also had a charming balcony that looked out over the street. Although we slept with the transom window opened each night, there was little to no car or pedestrian noise.Breakfasts were very good and had the usual choice of eggs, etc. Service was very prompt and courteous. If I had to find fault, I would say that the innkeeper seemed a bit rushed. Although she courteously answered our questions regarding sites, I got the impression she had a lot to do and wanted to end the conversation as quickly as possible. Perhaps there was some sort of staffing shortage, although no other level of service seemed lacking.All in all, I would definitely recommend the quaint inn to travelers staying any length of time. I truly felt like we enjoyed the best London had to offer at the Vicarage.	
Sep 18 2005	Great base for our weekend in London	The Vicarage Hotel was a great starting point for our first trip to England. We stayed in London for the weekend of our honeymoon, and this hotel was a nice, quiet place to return to after a day of sightseeing. The hotel is located on a quiet side street, about half way between the Notting Hill and High Street Kensington Tube stations, and was convenient to shops and restaurants.Our room was on the 1st floor, at the end of the main hall, and featured en suite lavatory and shower. We expected a small room, so we weren't disappointed by its cozy size. We were pleasently surprised by the good water pressure in the shower; there's nothing like a nice, hot, powerful shower at the end of a long day. If you prefer bed &amp; breakfasts to more traditional (and sterile) hotels, the Vicarage Hotel is a wonderful place to stay while in London.	
Sep 9 2005	Home away from home	We were looking for affordable but pleasant accomodations in London for our family of four which we found at the Vicarage. The hotel is a typical 3-4 story townhouse in a quiet residential neighboorhood near kensington park.There were restaurants, small shops, and a bus which ran all night long just one block away. We picked this neighboorhood as I wanted our family to feel safe away from the big city train stations. The neighboorhood felt safe but was only about 15 minutes away from any sight in London with a 1 GBP bus ticket. Another option is to take the 1 GBP tube to the other side of town to avoid the traffic during the day.The Vicarage provided a quad room with sink and shared toilet/shower in hallway for 102 GBP ($183) a night. Our room had a double bed and two single beds and was comfortable with a homey feel and very clean. The room was was on the third floor without an elevator but was not an issue for us. There were rooms on the first and second floors if the stairs would be a problem. The hotel had rooms with showers but we opted for the less expensive shared bath option. We never saw anyone else in the shared bath as there were only two other rooms on the floor.We were served a very nice hot breakfast prepared fresh for us which included eggs, sausage, tomatoe, toast, jam, coffee, and juice. Overall we were pleased with our choice and would come back again.	
Jun 8 2005	Very pleasant inn in a great location	My stay at the Vicarage Hotel was great. The location of the inn is fabulous - located in the shopping district near Kensington as well as Notting Hill. About a 5 minute walk from 2 Tube stops. Rooms and bathrooms were clean, the price was great, and the breakfast every morning was ample and good. Staff was courteous and helpful - went above and beyond the call of duty to accommodate me when I had to stay a few extra days due a stolen passport. I would highly recommend this to anyone looking for a nice B&amp;B experience in the London area.	
Nov 29 2004	High Marks to the Vicarage	I am a single traveler and have recently returned from a trip to London where I stayed at the Vicarage for the eighth time in the past ten years. The ambience and the location of the hotel are superb. Personally I have found the double room (without private shower) to be more suitable than a single room as the single room leaves one feeling almost claustrophobic - a shared trait among many London hotels. Not having a television in the rooms is actually a plus. You don't need to be concerened that someone in the next room will have fallen asleep at 3 a.m., with the TV volume turned up to high, thereby depriving you of precious sleep. The TV room, as others have pointed out, needs to be freshened up. The furniture is worn out beyond repair. Several of the people who congregated in the TV room one evening remarked that since there were no televisions in their rooms, the guests would be best served if the management invested in some type of satelite feed so that there were more viewing options in the TV lounge. It is my experience though that the TV room is often used primarily as an area for socialization rather than for actually watching TV. With more and more hotels and pubs in London opting for no smoking, hopefully, the complaints about smoking in the television room will soon be a thing of the past. The English Breakfast the staff of the Vicarage serves each morning is superb. The rooms are clean and in the eight times I've stayed at the hotel I have never had to wait to use a shower or rest room. As noted, if you are not opposed to staying in a hotel where there are no elevators and stair climbing is your only option, then the Vicarage is a good value for the money. The neighborhood around the hotel is safe. You have a post office and laundromat within a 5 minute walk of the hotel and are close to several Underground stations. For my money the Vicarage is the first and only option I would consider on any future trip to London.	
